{
  "answer": "**Charles Comte's strongest sentence** appears in *Traité de Législation* (Vol. I, Chap. 2): \"One can therefore, in treating the science of legislation, occupy oneself only with general and permanent laws, with those that exercise a great influence on the fate of nations; it is these whose causes we must investigate, whose nature we must determine, and whose effects we must expose.\"[^1]\n\n**Manu’s strongest sentence** appears in *Manusmṛti* (Chap. 2, verse 6): \"The entire Veda is the root-source of Dharma (the sacred law and eternal duty), as are *Smṛti* (the remembered tradition) and the conduct of those who know it, the practices of the virtuous, and one's own self-satisfaction.\"[^2]\n\nManu’s claim begs the question more severely. It assumes the Veda’s authority as self-evident to prove itself the source of *dharma*, without independent justification or empirical grounding in social conditions (a circular appeal to revelation). Comte’s rests on observable facts (causes and effects in \"things or in men\"), open to verification, though it too implies the value of analysis without fully proving why facts yield optimal laws.[^3]\n\n[^1]: Charles Comte, *Traité de Législation: VOL I*, Chap. 2 [paragraph](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-i-7e62a2/02-de-la-methode-analytique-appliquee-a-l-etude-de-la/translation/#p-c1dbae).\n\n[^2]: *Manusmṛti*, Chap. 2 [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/02/translation/#p-d70b97).\n\n[^3]: Charles Comte, *Traité de Législation: VOL I*, Chap. 2 [paragraph](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-i-7e62a2/02-de-la-methode-analytique-appliquee-a-l-etude-de-la/translation/#p-86b5df).",
